---
scope: src/components/DocsPage/
intent: >
  The docs surface composes the byte-faithful, timestamped, archivable
  canonical record of the AIDE methodology — the single web address
  where a reader, a patent examiner, the Wayback Machine, or a Fediverse
  post can point to for a specific version of a specific canonical doc.
  Its value depends entirely on the web version being demonstrably
  identical to the canonical source shipping with `aide_init` on disk.
  This surface's job is not to explain or teach AIDE in friendlier
  language than the canonical source — it is to render the canonical
  source, untouched, with citation metadata visible on every page.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - Every canonical doc page is byte-faithful to its source markdown file in the `.aide/` hub; a reader who diffs the rendered content region against the source finds zero semantic differences (markdown-to-HTML wrapping excepted).
    - Every canonical doc page carries a visible citation block in its header with publication date, source-file commit SHA, stable versioned URL, and Wayback archive URL.
    - Reading order on the docs section mirrors the canonical hub's progressive disclosure — `/docs` renders the `.aide/index.md` hub, and slug routes render individual canonical docs in the same order the hub lists them.
    - Every canonical doc page ends with a small install footer returning the reader to the landing's install path (Stripe docs-as-sales-channel pattern).
  undesired:
    - A CMS, dashboard, or any non-git edit surface for canonical doc content. Every contribution is a pull request against the canonical source and a rebuild. A dashboard-driven edit path creates drift and defeats the source-of-record claim.
    - Full-text or fuzzy search in v1. A search index that returns results in non-canonical order breaks the hub-crawl mental model; a title-only filter is acceptable if cheap, but full-text is specifically out of v1 scope.
    - Content rewrites for tone, typos, or "modernization." If the canonical source has a typo, the rendered page shows the typo until a PR is merged upstream. The docs surface is a renderer, not an author.
    - Plugin middleware that injects call-to-action boxes, "was this helpful?" widgets, related-articles footers, or comment sections into the rendered content body. These break byte-faithfulness and make the web version unquotable. The install footer is the one allowed exception because it sits outside the content region and serves the root spec's conversion outcome.
    - Hidden or stripped agent-facing callouts from canonical source files ("for agents: this file is a scaffold, not a reference"). Every human visitor sees exactly what every agent reader sees — the callouts stay.
    - In-place edits to published canonical doc pages. When a canonical doc is updated, the old version stays at its versioned URL and a separate linked errata note records the change. Quietly overwriting a published page breaks every citation that already exists.
    - A v1 quarterly byte-faithfulness re-verification audit is deferred to v1.1; this spec names the tripwire but does not deliver the audit. v1 ships build-time byte-faithfulness, enforced by the canonical-rendering service.
---

## Context

This surface's entire value proposition — patent priority, thought
leadership, quotable-in-Slack trustworthiness — rests on one invariant:
the web version and the shipped `.aide/` folder are literally the same
bytes. If that invariant is falsifiable, the priority claim and the
trust-the-docs claim both collapse together. Every decision on this
surface serves that invariant directly or is out of scope.

This surface is a composition layer. The real byte-faithfulness
enforcement lives in the canonical-rendering service
(`src/service/docs/renderCanonical/`) and the archival guarantees live
in the archive service (`src/service/docs/archive/`); this spec owns
the *visible shape* of the docs section — what a visitor sees, how
pages are navigated, where the citation metadata appears, and how the
section links back to the install path.

## Strategy

**Docs content is rendered from the git-tracked `.aide/` folder at
build time.** No CMS, no remote fetch, no middleware. The docs section
reads from the same folder `aide_init` installs on disk; the build is
a pure function of the git tree. Runtime reads are explicitly forbidden
(see root spec `outcomes.undesired`).

**Hub-first navigation mirrors the methodology's progressive disclosure.**
`/docs` renders the `.aide/index.md` hub as its landing, listing every
canonical doc in the same order the hub file lists them. Slug routes
(`/docs/aide-spec`, `/docs/progressive-disclosure`, etc.) render
individual canonical docs. There is no alternate reading order, no
"tutorials" section, no "getting started" path that is nowhere in the
canonical source, no "featured docs" block. The UI mirrors the hub
structure the agent sees.

**Citation block is visible, not hidden behind a click.** Every
canonical doc page header displays the publication date, source-file
commit SHA, stable versioned URL, and Wayback archive URL in a
DocHeader block above the content region. Cite-ability is the default,
not an opt-in. Readers can copy a versioned URL without clicking into
a menu.

**Errata are linked separate notes, never in-place edits.** When a
canonical doc is corrected, the prior version remains at its versioned
URL and a new errata note is linked from the old page's header. This
is the RFC/arXiv pattern — priority-date claims depend on frozen
published artifacts, and any mechanism that silently mutates a published
page breaks every existing citation. The implementor must not ship an
"Edit this page" button or any flow that mutates published content.

**Every canonical doc ends with an install footer.** A small
InstallFooter component below the content region returns the reader to
the landing's install path — this is the Stripe docs-as-sales-channel
pattern, and it is the one allowed exception to "nothing injected into
content." It sits below the content region, not inside it, so it
cannot be mistaken for part of the canonical source. The footer's
content is generated from the same typed install fixture the landing
uses (see install-content service spec) so it stays in sync with the
hero.

**No fuzzy search, no full-text search in v1.** Fuzzy search returning
results in non-canonical order breaks the hub-crawl mental model the
methodology teaches. A title-only filter is acceptable if the
implementor can add it cheaply; full-text search is specifically out
of scope for v1. The mental model the reader builds — hub → section
hub → content note — matches how an AIDE agent reads specs, and that
coherence is worth more than a search box.

**Page structure reuses shared primitives.** DocLayout, DocHeader,
DocToc, DocBody, and InstallFooter are the composition units. DocBody
is the only one that renders canonical content; the others are
chrome. DocHeader carries the citation block; DocToc is auto-generated
from the source file's heading structure; InstallFooter reuses the
shared CodeBlock / CopyButton primitives from the landing. No
domain-specific rendering lives in DocBody — it delegates to the
canonical-rendering service for the markdown-to-HTML transformation
and only concerns itself with the container and typography.

**The docs section is chrome around content, not content.** This spec
governs composition and navigation, not the byte-faithfulness guarantee
itself (that's the canonical-rendering service) and not the archival
guarantee (that's the archive service). A reader who finds a byte
drift or a missing archive should file a bug against the relevant
service, not against this surface — but the bug's symptom shows up
here, on the page they were reading, so this spec names those
invariants as tripwires it inherits.

## Good examples

A reader visits `https://aidemd.dev/docs`. The page renders
`.aide/index.md` converted to HTML, with the same doc list and the
same progressive-disclosure framing the canonical hub uses. Each link
in the hub resolves to `/docs/<name>` where the source file is
`.aide/<name>.md`.

A reader visits `https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec`. The page header
shows:

> **Published** 2026-04-11 · **Source commit** `a1b2c3d`
> **Cite as** `aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec@v20260411`
> **Archived** `web.archive.org/web/20260411140345/aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec`

The content region below renders `aide-spec.md` byte-for-byte. At the
bottom, separated from the content region by a visual break, a small
InstallFooter block reads "Install AIDE in your Claude Code project →"
and links to the landing's install section. The reader opens DevTools,
copies the content region text, diffs it against
`cat .aide/aide-spec.md`, and finds no semantic differences.

Two weeks later, the canonical spec is updated. The old version stays
at `/docs/aide-spec@v20260411` with an added errata banner linking to
the new version at `/docs/aide-spec@v20260425`. Neither URL has been
overwritten. A reader who cited the old version in a Slack thread
three weeks ago can still follow their link and see exactly what they
quoted, with a visible note that a newer version exists.

## Bad examples

`/docs/getting-started` exists with friendly prose that appears nowhere
in the canonical source ("Welcome to AIDE! Let's get started with your
first spec…"). A "What's new" banner sits at the top of `/docs` with
editable content and a last-updated timestamp that isn't tied to any
git commit. An "Edit this page" button links to a CMS dashboard. A
fuzzy search bar returning "AIDE for beginners" as the top result for
the query "progressive disclosure." A `/docs/aide-spec` page whose
typo was silently corrected in the web version — the canonical source
still has the typo, so the site and the installed methodology now
disagree and the source-of-record claim is broken.

A subtler failure: the canonical doc renders correctly but the header
displays only "Last updated: 2 weeks ago." No commit hash, no versioned
URL, no Wayback link. The page is byte-faithful but unquotable at
version-granularity, and the priority-date argument loses its anchor.

Another subtler failure: a "was this helpful?" widget appears below
every section, populated from a client-side analytics script. The
content region is byte-faithful in the HTML source but the visible
rendering interleaves widgets into the content flow, and a reader
diffing the rendered page against the canonical source finds
unexpected elements they cannot trace to the source.
